06408nam a22009375i 9781463241407DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20212021nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2020056096  a97814632414077 a10.31826/97814632414072doi  a(DE-B1597)575759  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ00aDS247.Q35bK69 2021 7aFOR0330002bisacsh04a492.7/71 aKozah, Mario, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBeth Qaṭraye :bA Lexical and Toponymical Survey /cMario Kozah, George Kiraz. 1aPiscataway, NJ : bGorgias Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (460 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aGorgias Eastern Christian Studies ;v5800tFrontmatter -- tTABLE OF CONTENTS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tPREFACE -- tTHE EDITORS -- tABBREVIATIONS -- tINTRODUCTION -- tA LEXICAL SURVEY OF QAṬRĀYĪTH -- tA TOPONYMICAL SURVEY OF BETH QAṬRAYE -- tTHE POLITICAL, ECONOMIC, AND SOCIAL SITUATION OF THE ISLANDS IN THE GULF REGION DURING THE THIRD AND FOURTH / NINTH AND TENTH CENTURIES -- tA RECONSTRUCTION OF THE LEXICON OF ḤENANISHOʿ BAR SAROSHWAY -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY OF WORKS CITED -- tINDICES0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBeth Qaṭraye, Syriac for “region of the Qataris,” is a term found in Syriac literature referring to the region of north-eastern Arabia, including modern-day Qatar and Bahrain, from the fourth to the ninth centuries.  Beth Qaṭraye was an important cultural, linguistic and religious crossroads in the pre-Islamic and early Islamic period, when it produced a number of important East-Syriac authors.  Scholarship has so far only focused on these Syriac authors and their writings rather than other aspects of Beth Qaṭraye.  This volume presents and analyzes information on the pre-Islamic and early Islamic historical geography and toponyms of the Beth Qaṭraye region as well as newly discovered vocabulary from a language referred to as Qaṭrāyīth (“in Qatari”) used by its inhabitants.  Based on analysis of this new data, Mario Kozah argues that Qaṭrāyīth is in fact a local Arabic dialect transliterated using Syriac letters. Thus, Qaṭrāyīth consists mostly of Arabic vocabulary (as well as a few Syriac and Pahlavi loanwords), and maintains mainly Arabic with some Syriac grammatical structures and lexical influence.  As such, it constitutes the oldest documented Arabic vernacular from the seventh-century Arabian Peninsula, revealing a language in rapid transformation.  The volume also includes a special chapter on the islands of the Gulf region according to Muslim sources by Saif Al-Murikhi and a unique reconstruction of the lexicon of Ḥenanishoʿ bar Seroshway (ca. 900) by George Kiraz.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aArabic languagexDialectszPersian Gulf Region. 0aArabic languagexDialectszQatar. 4aAncient Languages. 4aFOREIGN LANGUAGE STUDY. 4aGeneral. 7aFOREIGN LANGUAGE STUDY / Ancient Languages (see also Latin).2bisacsh1 aAbu-Husayn, Abdulrahim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAl Thani, Haya, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAl-Murikhi, Saif Shaheen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAl-Murikhi, Saif, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChamseddine, Abdul Rahman, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKiraz, George, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aKiraz, George, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKozah, Mario, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMichelson, David A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPotter,